  "text": "## LibreOffice Calc Formula Evaluation Chain\n\n### Overview\nThe formula evaluation in LibreOffice Calc flows through three main stages:\n1. **Parsing/Compilation**: Formula strings are parsed into tokens (bytecode)\n2. **Cell Storage**: Parsed formulas are stored in formula cells\n3. **Interpretation/Evaluation**: The bytecode is executed to produce results\n\n### 1. Formula Tokenizer/Compiler\n\n**Header File**: `sc/inc/compiler.hxx`\n**Implementation File**: `sc/source/core/tool/compiler.cxx`\n**Main Class**: `ScCompiler` (extends `formula::FormulaCompiler`)\n\nThe `ScCompiler` class (lines 181-280+ in compiler.hxx) is responsible for:\n- Parsing formula strings into tokens\n- Converting formula text into bytecode (token array)\n- Handling different formula grammars (ODS, XLSX, etc.)\n- Maintaining character classification and convention handling\n\nKey responsibilities:\n- Tokenization of formula expressions like `=SUM(A1:A10)`\n- Creation of `ScTokenArray` objects containing the compiled formula\n- Reference parsing and cell address conventions\n\n### 2. Formula Cell Type\n\n**Header File**: `sc/inc/formulacell.hxx`\n**Implementation File**: `sc/source/core/data/formulacell.cxx`\n**Main Class**: `ScFormulaCell`\n\nThe `ScFormulaCell` class (starting at line 150+ in formulacell.hxx) represents a spreadsheet cell containing a formula. Key features:\n- **Constructors** (lines 197-225): Various constructors accepting formula strings, token arrays, or formula grammar\n- **Interpret()** method (line 268): Triggers formula evaluation\n- **SetDirty()** method (line 235): Marks cell for recalculation\n- **Compile()** methods (lines 255-262): Parse formula string into tokens\n- **InterpretTail()** method (line 184): Low-level interpretation logic\n\nThe `ScFormulaCell` holds:\n- The compiled token array (`ScTokenArray`)\n- The cell address (`ScAddress aPos`, line 190)\n- Formula result and error state\n- Recalculation flags\n\n### 3. Formula Bytecode Interpreter\n\n**Header File**: `sc/source/core/inc/interpre.hxx`\n**Implementation Files**: Split across multiple files:\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr1.cxx` - Core interpreter\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr2.cxx` - Function implementations\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr3.cxx` - More functions\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr4.cxx` - Database/external functions\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr5.cxx` - Statistical functions\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr6.cxx` - Additional functions\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr7.cxx` - Matrix/array functions\n- `sc/source/core/tool/interpr8.cxx` - More specialized functions\n\n**Main Class**: `ScInterpreter` (starting at line 197 in interpre.hxx)\n\nThe `ScInterpreter` class implements bytecode execution:\n- **Constructor** (line 1126): Initializes interpreter with cell, document, context, and token array\n- **Interpret()** method (line 1138): Main entry point that executes the formula and returns result\n- **Push/Pop operations**: Stack-based operations for formula evaluation\n- **Function implementations**: Methods implementing each formula function (SUM, AVERAGE, etc.)\n- **Type conversions**: Handles value conversions between types\n\nInternal state:\n- `pArr`: Token array (line 244)\n- `pStack`: Evaluation stack for operands (line 257)\n- `nGlobalError`: Error code tracking (line 258)\n- `sp`: Stack pointer (line 259)\n- `pMyFormulaCell`: Reference to the cell being evaluated (line 253)\n- `mrContext`: Interpreter context containing document reference (line 245)\n\n### 4. Recalculation Scheduling & Mode\n\n**Definition File**: `include/formula/tokenarray.hxx` (lines 59-69)\n**Enum**: `ScRecalcMode`\n\nThe `ScRecalcMode` enum defines when formulas should be recalculated:\n```cpp\nenum class ScRecalcMode : sal_uInt8\n{\n    ALWAYS         = 0x01,  // exclusive, always recalculate\n    ONLOAD_MUST    = 0x02,  // exclusive, always after load\n    ONLOAD_ONCE    = 0x04,  // exclusive, once after load (import)\n    ONLOAD_LENIENT = 0x08,  // exclusive, lenient after load\n    NORMAL         = 0x10,  // exclusive, normal mode\n    FORCED         = 0x20,  // combined, force even if not visible\n    ONREFMOVE      = 0x40,  // combined, if reference moved\n    EMask          = ...     // mask of exclusive bits\n}\n```\n\n**Usage**: `ScFormulaCell::AddRecalcMode()` (line 388 in formulacell.hxx, implemented at line 2649 in formulacell.cxx)\n- Marks formula cells for recalculation based on the mode\n- Controls when cells are added to the recalculation queue\n- Determines if cell results are volatile (always recalculate) or stable (only recalc when dirty)\n\n### Evaluation Chain Flow\n\n**Example: `=SUM(A1:A10)` enters a cell**\n\n1. **User enters formula** → `ScFormulaCell` constructor receives formula string\n2. **Parsing Phase**: `ScCompiler::ParseFormula()` is called\n   - Formula string is tokenized into operations and operands\n   - Result: `ScTokenArray` with compiled tokens\n   - Reference ranges (A1:A10) are identified and stored\n   \n3. **Storage**: `ScFormulaCell` stores the token array and registers listeners for referenced cells\n\n4. **Recalculation Decision**: `ScRecalcMode` determines if immediate recalc needed\n   - NORMAL mode: Wait for dependency changes\n   - ALWAYS mode: Recalculate every iteration\n   - ONLOAD_MUST: Recalculate after file load\n\n5. **Evaluation Phase**: `ScFormulaCell::Interpret()` is called\n   - Creates `ScInterpreter` instance with token array\n   - Calls `ScInterpreter::Interpret()`\n   - Interpreter walks token array, executing operations\n   - Stack-based evaluation: pushes operands, executes functions\n\n6. **SUM Implementation**: In interpreter's SUM handler\n   - Processes range A1:A10\n   - Iterates cells, accumulates values\n   - Returns sum result\n\n7. **Result Storage**: Result stored in `ScFormulaCell`\n   - Sets result type and value\n   - Updates format index if needed\n   - Broadcasts change notification to dependent cells\n\n### Key Implementation Details\n\n- **Thread Safety**: `ScInterpreterContext` provides thread-safe access to document data\n- **Error Handling**: `FormulaError` enum tracks calculation errors (division by zero, circular refs, etc.)\n- **Matrix Support**: `ScMatrix` handles array formulas and matrix operations\n- **External References**: Support for cross-document and cross-sheet references\n- **Performance**: Multiple interpreter instances split across 8 implementation files for code organization\n"
